specs/xena/expose-cinder-user-visible-ex.message:
I think today the extra specs are only revealed via volume types (cinder client 'cinder extra-specs-list' command actually lists the volume types and there is no 'cinder extra-specs-show' command).  One could reasonably argue for a direct extra specs endpoint but that is more change than needed to get what we need.

I think we need just the two API calls that Brian cites above.  Today the second is Forbidden to non-admin users and the first returns an empty set of extra_specs to non-admin users.  With the implementation of this spec neither will be Forbidden to non-admin users.  Admin users and non-admin users will both get a set of extra specs in the API response but the contents of that set will be restricted (via REST view) to user-visible extra specs for non-admin users.

The API reference [1] currently shows these response examples:

   GET /v3/{project_id}/types/{volume_type_id}/extra_specs

     {
        "extra_specs": {
            "capabilities": "gpu"
         }
     }

   GET /v3/{project_id}/types/{volume_type_id}/extra_specs/{key}

    {
        "capabilities": "gpu"
    }

We should change these to have Cinder rather than Nova content.  For example, assuming
a volume-type with two extra_specs, the abstract, backend-independent, user-visible ``multiattach`` and the backend revealing ``volume_backend_name``, then for this request

    GET /v3/{project_id}/types/{volume_type_id}/extra_specs

an administrator might see:

    {
        "extra_specs": {
            "multiattach": True,
            "volume_backend_name": "ExpensiveSecetiveVendor"
         }
     }

whereas a non-administrator would see:

    {
        "extra_specs": {
            "multiattach": True,
         }
     }

For

   GET /v3/{project_id}/types/{volume_type_id}/extra_specs/multipath

administrators and non-administrators would both see:

    {
        "multiattach": True
    }


For 

   GET /v3/{project_id}/types/{volume_type_id}/extra_specs/volume_backend_name

an administrator would see:

    {
        "volume_backend_name": "ExpensiveSecretiveVendor"
    }

whereas non-admins would get a 404 response:

    {"itemNotFound": 
      {"code": 404, "message": "Volume Type 86107076-d7e4-4c16-8cb3-da3fb910d628 has no extra specs with key volume_backend_name."
      }
    }

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/api-ref/block-storage/v3/index.html#volume-types-types

Three endpoints are affected:

1. /v3/{project_id}/types/{volume_type_id}
2. /v3/{project_id}/types/{volume_type_id}/extra_specs
3. /v3/{project_id}/types/{volume_type_id}/extra_specs/{key}

I already had 1. in mind, and now that I'm familiar with 2 and 3 I see they also provide visibility to the same data, so it makes sense to relax the policy to allow users to use those endpoints. The data returned will be consistent with what we've discussed: users will see the 'user visible' specs and admins will see all of them.

I will post an update with examples.

